---

🧠 Big Picture (What you’re achieving)

Right now your app likely connects like this:

App → Oracle DB (TCP, NOT encrypted ❌)

After this setup:

App → Oracle Wallet → Oracle DB (TCPS, encrypted ✅)

👉 Oracle Wallet = trust store + SSL configuration for Oracle client


---

🔧 STEP-BY-STEP (Detailed Explanation)


---

✅ STEP 1: Create Wallet Directory

mkdir -p /opt/oracle/wallet
cd /opt/oracle/wallet

🔍 What this does:

Creates a folder to store:

Certificates

Wallet files



🧠 Why:

Oracle client needs a secure location to read SSL config



---

✅ STEP 2: Create Wallet

orapki wallet create -wallet /opt/oracle/wallet -pwd MyWallet@123 -auto_login

🔍 What happens:

This creates 2 files:

File	Purpose

ewallet.p12	Main encrypted wallet
cwallet.sso	Auto-login wallet (no password needed at runtime)



---

🧠 Why this is needed:

Oracle uses wallet instead of Java truststore

It stores:

Trusted certificates

SSL config




---

⚠️ Important:

-auto_login is critical for servers

Without it → app will fail (needs password)



---

✅ STEP 3: Get Certificates (VERY IMPORTANT)

👉 You need from DBA/network team:

Server certificate

Intermediate certificate

Root certificate


🔍 Example files:

server-cert.pem
intermediate.pem
root.pem


---

🧠 Why:

SSL works on trust chain:

Your App → trusts Root → validates DB certificate

If missing → ❌ connection fails


---

✅ STEP 4: Add Certificates to Wallet

Add root cert:

orapki wallet add -wallet /opt/oracle/wallet -trusted_cert -cert root.pem -pwd MyWallet@123

Add intermediate:

orapki wallet add -wallet /opt/oracle/wallet -trusted_cert -cert intermediate.pem -pwd MyWallet@123

Add server cert (if provided):

orapki wallet add -wallet /opt/oracle/wallet -trusted_cert -cert server-cert.pem -pwd MyWallet@123


---

🔍 What happens:

Certificates get stored inside wallet



---

🧠 Why:

Oracle must trust the DB server

Without this → SSL handshake fails



---

✅ STEP 5: Verify Wallet

orapki wallet display -wallet /opt/oracle/wallet

🔍 Output should show:

Trusted Certificates ✔



---

🧠 Why:

Ensures wallet is correctly populated



---

✅ STEP 6: Configure sqlnet.ora

📍 Location:

$ORACLE_HOME/network/admin/sqlnet.ora

Add:

WALLET_LOCATION = (SOURCE = (METHOD = FILE) (METHOD_DATA = (DIRECTORY = /opt/oracle/wallet)))
SSL_CLIENT_AUTHENTICATION = FALSE


---

🔍 What this does:

Setting	Meaning

WALLET_LOCATION	Where wallet is stored
SSL_CLIENT_AUTHENTICATION = FALSE	No client cert needed



---

🧠 Why:

Tells Oracle client: 👉 “Use this wallet for SSL connections”



---

✅ STEP 7: Configure tnsnames.ora

📍 Same directory:

MYDB_TCPS =
  (DESCRIPTION =
    (ADDRESS = (PROTOCOL = TCPS)(HOST = your-db-host)(PORT = 2484))
    (CONNECT_DATA =
      (SERVICE_NAME = your_service)
    )
  )


---

🔍 Key part:

PROTOCOL = TCPS


---

🧠 Why:

TCPS = TCP + SSL encryption

Without this → still insecure



---

✅ STEP 8: Test Connection (CRITICAL STEP)

sqlplus username/password@MYDB_TCPS


---

🔍 What happens:

Oracle client:

1. Reads wallet


2. Loads certificates


3. Establishes SSL connection





---

🧠 Why:

This confirms: ✔ Wallet correct
✔ Certificates valid
✔ DB supports TCPS



---

✅ STEP 9: Use in Spring Boot

Option 1 (Preferred)

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:oracle:thin:@MYDB_TCPS


---

Option 2 (Direct TCPS)

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:oracle:thin:@(DESCRIPTION=
 (ADDRESS=(PROTOCOL=tcps)(HOST=host)(PORT=2484))
 (CONNECT_DATA=(SERVICE_NAME=service))
)


---

🧠 What happens:

App uses Oracle client config

Wallet is automatically picked



---

⚠️ COMMON ERRORS (DETAILED)


---

❌ ORA-29024 (Certificate issue)

Cause:

Missing root/intermediate cert


Fix:

👉 Add full chain again


---

❌ PKIX Path Building Failed (Java issue)

Cause:

JVM doesn’t trust cert


Fix:

keytool -import -trustcacerts -alias oracleDB \
-file root.pem \
-keystore $JAVA_HOME/lib/security/cacerts


---

❌ Handshake Failure

Cause:

TLS mismatch OR DB not configured for TCPS


👉 Ask DBA:

“Is TCPS enabled on port 2484?”



---

🧪 How Auditor Thinks

They will check:

Check	Expected

Protocol	TCPS
Port	2484
Encryption	Enabled
Certificates	Valid



